RESNA 2017 STUDENT DESIGN COMPETITION

Rehabilitation Engineering and Assistive Technology Society of North America (RESNA) designed the Student Design Competition (SDC) to promote and foster innovative and creative design of assistive technology hardware and/or software used by or in support of individuals with disabilities. In addition to inspiring students to work on design projects which will enhance the independence of individuals with disabilities, it is also designed to encourage, support and mentor students in various disciplines to become aware of and involved in the assistive technology (AT) and rehabilitation engineering fields. We received over 70 submissions for the 2017 SDC. In order to facilitate the expansion of the competition, RESNA is continuing to use a dynamic, rich media website (http://aac-rerc.psu.edu/wordpressmu/RESNA-SDC) to support archival processes of all submissions.

Eight teams were named as finalists, and six of these teams attended the conference and professionally presented an oral defense of their design. The 2017 annual RESNA Conference was held at the Hilton Riverside in New Orleans, Louisiana, July 28-30, 2017 with approximately 450 individual attendees. The finalists presented their work at the RESNA Developers? Showcase, an interactive forum where conference participants provided informal interaction with each student team. Presentation and judging of the finalist teams took place within the conference, in a 2-hour session open to all conference attendees.  All teams were recognized during the RESNA Awards Luncheon and presented Certificates for their SDC participation at the Developers? Showcase.

Student projects were evaluated on the following criteria:

Design adequately addresses problem posed by the student/client team;
Prototype uses sound engineering or design approaches, which promote safety and use by targeted client/population;
Creativity is evident in the proposed solution, and it represents a new addition to the field of assistive technology;
Students have evaluated and/or validated the prototype in an iterative way with their targeted client/population;
Students are capable of communicating their ideas well, within structured guidelines, without errors or omissions;
Prototype is functional, as viewed in their product video.


Several Press Releases announcing the outcomes of the Student Design Competition were produced and sent to various media outlets including students? local newspapers, as well as various list serves, via LinkedIn, to disability organizations and through RESNA NewsBriefs. https://www.resna.org/news-events/annual-meeting/students/student-design-competition/2017-student-design-competition. A list of the finalists in included in the 2017 Conference Proceedings.

RESNA views this design competition as a means to expand the quantity and quality of the number of professionals who enter the field of rehabilitation engineering and assistive technology. The RESNA SDC provides an opportunity extending beyond this annual conference. In addition, the enhancements of video/audio streaming and web-page developments will hopefully increase the participation of more diverse students in the future.

